Reference-contexts: In this paper, two methods are examined for using multiple access methods for building a high-speed optical network. 1.1 Access methods to be examined The first access method to be examined is Wavelength Division Multiplexing (WDM). This is the approach used by a wideband optical consortium led by Bell-core <ref> [3] </ref>, as well as other such consortia. A summary of the Bellcore optical network proposal will be given. The second method to be examined is Code Division Multiple Access (CDMA) methods. These are systems which allow sharing based on special encoding for each user or communications channel. <p> The latest enabling development is the erbium-doped fiber amplifier, which can amplify optical signals over a range of wavelengths. This enables all-optical amplification systems rather than electrical detection and regeneration. 2.1 Proposed access methods The WDM Optical Network proposed by Brackett et al <ref> [3] </ref> utilizes separate wavelengths to access the network, and special wavelength switchers to route signals between portions of the network. <p> A WDM system in a broadcast star network is similar to the CB radio. One common wavelength channel can be used negotiate for direct connections on other wavelengths. 3.1 Architecture of Bellcore proposal The Optical Network Consortium led by Bellcore <ref> [3] </ref> approaches high capacity optical networks by the use of WDM technology, as shown in Figure 2. While it is possible to fit hundreds or even thousands of distinct channels into a fiber, Brackett et al propose just to use eight wavelengths throughout the entire network.
